<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="15.-Evaluation-Metrics">15. Evaluation Metrics<a class="anchor-link" href="#15.-Evaluation-Metrics">&#182;</a></h2><p><strong>Confusion Matrix: False Alarms</strong></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># just a helper function for easier youtube call</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">strip_url</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">url</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">url</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">replace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;https://youtu.be/&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[2]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">IPython.display</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">YouTubeVideo</span>
<span class="n">YouTubeVideo</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">strip_url</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;https://youtu.be/611qWzIxGmU&#39;</span><span class="p">))</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area">

<div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[2]:</div>



<div class="output_html rendered_html output_subarea output_execute_result">

        <iframe
            width="400"
            height="300"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/611qWzIxGmU"
            frameborder="0"
            allowfullscreen
        ></iframe>
        
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Answer is 1. And note the asymmtry. We have this as one type of false alarm, say PN (that is, burglary predicted when its not), and other, NP, where there is no alarm, when actual burglary happenning.</p>
<p>Obviously we would want to reduce no of NP types, as burglary would have happened while weare not aware which is much costlier than having PN type false alarms (just alarming us, when acutally no burglary happened).</p>
<p>Thus the nature of problem may push us towards skewing our prediction (here, for ex, boundary line) so that NP types are minimized (even if that means, increasing PN types)</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><u>**Classifying Chavez Correctly 1**</u></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[3]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="n">url</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;https://youtu.be/0PFq8zoaNWU&#39;</span>
<span class="n">YouTubeVideo</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">strip_url</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">url</span><span class="p">))</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area">

<div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[3]:</div>



<div class="output_html rendered_html output_subarea output_execute_result">

        <iframe
            width="400"
            height="300"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/0PFq8zoaNWU"
            frameborder="0"
            allowfullscreen
        ></iframe>
        
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>What is the probability that HC would be classifed correctly by our learning algorithm?</strong></p>
<p>This is a little bit tricky question. Remember the columns are also in same order, but indicating predictions. So we need to look carefully.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="HC.png"></p>
<p>The row could give us total number of HC (for eg, for cell (row,col) = (6,2)), value is 3, which means, 3 times Hugo Chavez has been predicted as Colin Powell. So there goes 3 HC as CP. Similarly for other cells in that same row. Totally no of HCs predicted as others and also himself, which is 16.</p>
<p>The col 6 could give us, when exactly HC was predicted as HC himself, correctly. That is 10 times.</p>
<p>Probability of something is  fraction of no of times that something happens to all related outcomes.</p>
<p>Probability of <em>predicting HC</em> would be fraction of no of times HC predicted correctly, to total no of HC predictions (all <em>HC</em> predictions including correct and wrong)</p>
<p>$$ \displaystyle p(\text{HC predicted correctly) = }\frac{{n(\text{HC predicted correctly)}}}{{n(\text{HC}\text{ predicted)}}}=\frac{{10}}{{16}}=0.625$$</p>
<p>As we would see shortly , this is called <strong>Recall</strong></p>
<p><br><div style="background-color:'#E3F2FD;  padding: 10px 10px 10px 10px;">
$$ \displaystyle \text{Recall =}\frac{{(\text{prediction is reality)}}}{{(\text{prediction is reality)+(prediction is not reality ; type 1)}}}=\frac{{\text{True Positive}}}{{\text{True Positive +}\text{ False Negative}}}$$
</div><br>
The <code>type 1 prediction not being reality</code> is <strong>no of times algorithm predicting wrongly as others while it was HC in reality</strong>. This is False Negative.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><u>**Classifying Chavez Correctly 2**</u></p>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="n">url</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;https://youtu.be/HWW9BNHnPo0&#39;</span>
<span class="n">YouTubeVideo</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">strip_url</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">url</span><span class="p">))</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>Given predictor says its HC, what is probability is it truly HC?</strong></p>
<p>This is another tricky question, and no need not go in to Bayesian conditional probability yet. The confusion matrix itself could provide the answer.<br>
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="HC2.png"><br>
The 6th col in confusion matrix is our algo predicting Hugo(?!). For eg, cell(row,col) = (2,6) indicate value as 0, which means, algo predicted as HC 0 times, when it is actually Colin Powell.</p>
<p>So this way, we can see, our algo does not predict any one else as HC, except HC himself. Thus probability is 1.</p>
<p>$$ \displaystyle p(\text{True HC  }\text{ }\!\! | \!\!\text{ }\text{ predicted as HC) = }\frac{{n(\text{predicted as HC and its True HC)}}}{{n(\text{predicted as HC)}}}=\frac{{10}}{{10}}=1$$</p>
<p>As we would see shortly , this is called <strong>Precision</strong></p>
<p><br><div style="background-color:'#E3F2FD;  padding: 10px 10px 10px 10px;">
$$ \displaystyle \text{Precision =}\frac{{(\text{prediction is reality)}}}{{(\text{prediction is reality)+(prediction is not reality ; type 2)}}}=\frac{{\text{True Positive}}}{{\text{True Positive +}\text{ False Positive}}}$$
</div><br></p>
<p>The <code>type 2 prediction not being reality</code> is <strong>no of times algorithm predicting wrongly as HC while it was others in reality</strong>. This is False Positive.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><br><div style="background-color:'#E3F2FD; padding: 10px 10px 10px 10px;">
Remember, True Positives, or False Positives or False Negatives are relative to the <strong>subject</strong> in focus. Always.</p>
<p>Here the subject is <strong>Tony Blair</strong></p>
<p>So,</p>
<p>True Positive =&gt; Algorithm predicts Tony Blair and Reality is Tony Blair<br>
False Positive =&gt; Algorithm predicts Tony Blair but Reality is others<br>
False Negative =&gt; Algorithm predicts others but Reality is Tony Blair</p>
<p>&lt;/div&gt;<br></p>
<p>For True positives, thus, its 26
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="True%20Positives.png"></p>

<p><strong>False Negatives in Eigenfaces</strong></p>
<p>In same line of thought..
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="False%20Negatives.png"></p>

</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">

<p><strong>Practicing TP, FP, FN with Rumsfeld</strong></p>
<p>In same line of thought..<br>
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Rum.png"></p>
<p>TP = 25<br>
FP = 1+1 = 2<br>
FN = 1+8+2 = 11</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<div style="background-color:'#E3F2FD; padding: 10px 10px 10px 10px;">
Remember, the generalized notion  <br><br>

Given a **Subject**,  

True Positive => Algorithm predicts **Subject** and Reality is **Subject**  
False Positive => Algorithm predicts **Subject** but Reality is **others**  
False Negative => Algorithm predicts **others** but Reality is **Subject**    

<br>
**Positive** => always predicting the **Subject** and Negative, otherwise.  
**True** => always Reality inline with **Prediction** and False, otherwise  
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Applying-Metrics-to-Your-POI-Identifier">Applying Metrics to Your POI Identifier<a class="anchor-link" href="#Applying-Metrics-to-Your-POI-Identifier">&#182;</a></h2><p>Udacity:<br>

Recall that at the end of that project, your identifier had an accuracy (on the test set) of 0.724. Not too bad, right? Let's dig into your predictions a little more carefully.</p>

</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[8]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># evaluate_poi_identifier.py</span>
<span class="c1">#!/usr/bin/python</span>

<span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Starter code for the evaluation mini-project.</span>
<span class="sd">    Start by copying your trained/tested POI identifier from</span>
<span class="sd">    that which you built in the validation mini-project.</span>

<span class="sd">    This is the second step toward building your POI identifier!</span>

<span class="sd">    Start by loading/formatting the data...</span>
<span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>

<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pickle</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">sys</span>
<span class="n">sys</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">path</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;../tools/&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">feature_format</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">featureFormat</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">targetFeatureSplit</span>

<span class="n">data_dict</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pickle</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">load</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">open</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;../17. Final Project/final_project_dataset.pkl&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;r&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">features_list</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;poi&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;salary&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">featureFormat</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data_dict</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">features_list</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">labels</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">features</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">targetFeatureSplit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1">### your code goes here </span>
</pre></div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[9]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># code from last section &#39;validation&#39;</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">tree</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn.metrics</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">accuracy_score</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">classify</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">features_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">labels_train</span><span class="p">):</span>

    <span class="c1">### your code goes here--should return a trained decision tree classifer</span>
    <span class="n">X</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">features_train</span>
    <span class="n">Y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">labels_train</span>
    <span class="n">clf</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">tree</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DecisionTreeClassifier</span><span class="p">()</span>
    <span class="n">clf</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">clf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">X</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">Y</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">clf</span>

<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">cross_validation</span>
<span class="n">features_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">features_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">labels_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">labels_test</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">cross_validation</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">train_test_split</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">features</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">labels</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">test_size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">random_state</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">42</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># train</span>
<span class="n">clf</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">classify</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">features_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">labels_train</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># now we make sensible choice..</span>

<p><strong>Unpacking Into Precision and Recall</strong></p>
<p>Udacity: As you may now see, having imbalanced classes like we have in the Enron dataset (many more non-POIs than POIs) introduces some special challenges, namely that you can just guess the more common class label for every point, not a very insightful strategy, and still get pretty good accuracy!</p>
<p>Precision and recall can help illuminate your performance better. Use the precision_score and recall_score available in sklearn.metrics to compute those quantities.</p>
<p>What's the precision?</p>

</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn.metrics</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">precision_score</span>
<span class="n">precision_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labels_test</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">labels_pred</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<p>(Note: you may see a message like UserWarning: The precision and recall are equal to zero for some labels. Just like the message says, there can be problems in computing other metrics (like the F1 score) when precision and/or recall are zero, and it wants to warn you when that happens.)</p>
<p>Obviously this isn't a very optimized machine learning strategy (we haven't tried any algorithms besides the decision tree, or tuned any parameters, or done any feature selection), and now seeing the precision and recall should make that much more apparent than the accuracy did.</p>

<span class="n">true_labels</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">count</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">j</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">zip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">true_labels</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">):</span>

        <span class="n">count</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>

<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">j</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">zip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">true_labels</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="mi">0</span> <span class="ow">and</span> <span class="n">j</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>  <span class="c1"># both actual and predicted are false</span>

$$ \displaystyle \text{Precision =}\frac{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)}}}{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)+(Prediction : Subject, Reality : Others)}}}=\frac{{\text{True Positive}}}{{\text{True Positive + False Positive}}}$$

<span class="n">true_labels</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="n">TP_count</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">FP_count</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">reality</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">prediction</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">zip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">true_labels</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">):</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># TP is both Pred and Reality, Subject</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">reality</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="ow">and</span> <span class="n">prediction</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">TP_count</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># FP is Prediction is Subject, Reality otherwise.</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">reality</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">0</span> <span class="ow">and</span> <span class="n">prediction</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">FP_count</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
        
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">__future__</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">division</span>  <span class="c1"># python 2 limitation</span>
<span class="n">Precision</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">TP_count</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">TP_count</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">FP_count</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">Precision</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>Recall</strong></p>
<p><br><div style="background-color:'#E3F2FD;  padding: 10px 10px 10px 10px;">
$$ \displaystyle \text{Precision =}\frac{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)}}}{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)+(Prediction : Others, Reality : Subject)}}}=\frac{{\text{True Positive}}}{{\text{True Positive + False Negative}}}$$
</div><br></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[21]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="n">TP_count</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">FN_count</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">reality</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">prediction</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">zip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">true_labels</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">):</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># TP is both Pred and Reality, Subject</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">reality</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="ow">and</span> <span class="n">prediction</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">TP_count</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># FN is Prediction is Others, Reality otherwise.</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">reality</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="ow">and</span> <span class="n">prediction</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">FN_count</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
        
<span class="n">Recall</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">TP_count</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">TP_count</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">FN_count</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">Recall</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Making-Sense-of-Metrics-1">Making Sense of Metrics 1<a class="anchor-link" href="#Making-Sense-of-Metrics-1">&#182;</a></h2><p>Udacity: 'My true positive rate is high, which means that when a ___ is present in the test data, I am good at flagging him or her.'</p>
<p>Choices: POI, non-POI</p>
<p>Ans: True Positive =&gt; Both Prediction and Reality are Subject. So if this is more, then we are good at predicting the POI.</p>
<h2 id="Making-Sense-of-Metrics-2">Making Sense of Metrics 2<a class="anchor-link" href="#Making-Sense-of-Metrics-2">&#182;</a></h2><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="making%20sense.png"></p>
<p>Let us recall, Recall and Precision definitions, rewrite them so as to make some sense, relatable to the question in hand.</p>
<hr>

<p>$$ \displaystyle \begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {\text{Precision}} \\ {=\dfrac{{\text{True Positive}}}{{\text{True Positive + False Positive}}}=\dfrac{{\text{TP}}}{{\text{TP+FP}}}} \\ {\text{=}\dfrac{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)}}}{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)+(Prediction : Subject, Reality : Others)}}}} \\ \begin{array}{l}=\dfrac{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)}}}{{\text{Prediction: Subject (irrespective of Reality)}}}\\\end{array} \end{array}$$</p>
<hr>

<p>$$ \displaystyle \begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {\text{Recall}} \\ {=\dfrac{{\text{True Positive}}}{{\text{True Positive + False Negative}}}=\dfrac{{\text{TP}}}{{\text{TP+FN}}}} \\ {\text{=}\dfrac{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)}}}{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)+(Prediction : Others, Reality : Subject)}}}} \\ {=\dfrac{{(\text{Prediction : Subject, Reality : Subject)}}}{{\text{Reality: Subject (irrespective of Prediction)}}}} \end{array}$$</p>
<p>Let us talk about influence of performance on these parameters (so we could understand the inverse).</p>
<p>Take a look at both in short form again.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>$$ \displaystyle \text{Precision = }\frac{{\text{TP}}}{{\text{TP+FP}}}\text{            Recall=}\frac{{\text{TP}}}{{\text{TP+FN}}}$$</p>
<p><br><div style="background-color:'#E3F2FD;  padding: 10px 10px 10px 10px;">
One can note, the <strong>TP</strong> value, if increasing or decreasing is going to have <strong>same effect</strong> on both Precision and Recall values. If TP increases, both precision and recall would increase (provided FP and FN not varying). So a high TP could not be indicative measure for both high precision and high recall.</p>
<p>Thus, let us consider the other two influencers in the equation. <strong>FP and FN</strong>.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Now one could easily observe, <strong>increasing FP decreases Precision</strong>. So higher the False Positives, lower the Precision. In other words, higher the <code>'prediction: subject, reality: others'</code>, lower the precsion.  For case in our hand, <code>'prediction: POI, reality: non-POI'</code>. So low precision indicates more non-POI are wrongly flagged as POI. <strong>Lower the precision, more non-POIs get wrongly flagged as POIs</strong> which is naturally not desired, as innocent non-POIs could be scrutized as POIs.</p>
<p>So generally, we prefer, high Precision (so less non-Subjects scrutinized unnecessarily)</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Similarly, <strong>increasing FN decreases Recall</strong>. So higher the False Negatives, lower the Recall. In other words, higher the <code>'prediction: others, reality: subject'</code>, lower the Recall.  For case in our hand, <code>'prediction: non-POI, reality: POI'</code>. So low recall indicates more POIs wrongly flagged as non-POIs.  <strong>Lower the recall, more POIs get wrongly flagged as non-POIs</strong> which is naturally not desired, as POIs could escape.</p>
<p>So generally, we also prefer, high Recall (so less Subjects could 'escape')</p>
<p>&lt;/div&gt;</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now, coming to question, author says these..</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><em>My identifier does not have a great X but it does have good Y.</em></p>
<p>This could indicate, out of 3 candidates, <strong>P (Precision), R (Recall), F1</strong>, two are quantified, out of which, one is low, another is high.</p>
<p><hr><br></p>
<p><em>That means, nearly everytime a POI shows up in test set, I am able to identify him or her</em></p>
<p>This could mean <strong>high TP</strong>. nearly everytime reality is POI, prediction is POI. So could mean, <strong>high P or high R or high F1</strong>.<br>
This could also mean, <strong>low FN</strong>. That is, <code>predicting some one as non-POI while in reality he/she is POI, is low</code>. Thus <strong>low FN</strong> or <strong>high recall</strong>.  (less instances of Prediction: non-POI, Reality: POI)
I fainted.</p>
<p><hr><br></p>
<p><em>The cost of this is that, sometimes I get false positives, where non-POIs get flagged</em></p>
<p>That is <code>predicting some one as POI, while in reality he/she is non-POI, is increased</code> as a cost for tuning the algorithm for high recall.<br>
That is, <strong>high FP</strong> or <strong>low Precision</strong> (more instances of Prediction: POI, Reality: non-POI).</p>
<p>The author has tuned the algorithm to reduce instances of POIs getting flagged as non-POIs (or minimizing POIs escaping), at the cost of more non-POIs getting flagged as POIs.</p>
<hr>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Making-Sense-of-Metrics-3">Making Sense of Metrics 3<a class="anchor-link" href="#Making-Sense-of-Metrics-3">&#182;</a></h2><p>'My identifier doesn't have great _, but it does have good __. That means that whenever a POI gets flagged in my test set, I know with a lot of confidence that it's very likely to be a real POI and not a false alarm. On the other hand, the price I pay for this is that I sometimes miss real POIs, since I'm effectively reluctant to pull the trigger on edge cases.'</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><br></p>
<p><em>My identifier does not have a great X but it does have good Y.</em></p>
<p>This could indicate, out of 3 candidates, <strong>P (Precision), R (Recall), F1</strong>, two are quantified, out of which, one is low, another is high.</p>
<p><hr><br></p>
<p><em>That means that whenever a POI gets flagged in my test set, I know with a lot of confidence that it's very likely to be a real POI and not a false alarm</em></p>
<p>Here, prediction: POI, more of reality: POI, less of reality: non-POI<br>
In other words, more of (prediction: POI, reality: POI), less of (prediction: POI, reality: non-POI). 
When prediction is subject for both cases of reality given, we could directly head to Precision. 
Thus, less of (prediction: POI, reality: non-POI) implies less False Positives, that is  <strong>decreased FP or high Precision</strong>.</p>
<p><hr><br></p>
<p><em>On the other hand, the price I pay for this is that <strong>I sometimes miss real POIs</strong>, since I'm effectively reluctant to pull the trigger on edge cases</em></p>
<p>Missing real POIs, implies prediction: non-POI, while reality: POI. Its False Negative. Its said as the price paid, implying, False Negative increased as a result of tuning.  False Negative because Algorithm predicts others, while reality is Subject. Thus <strong>increased FN or low Recall</strong></p>

</div>
